From 61966e6c2b7c75ca2f11c84bcd56ed99e2c2c0c7 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Yalu Cai <yalucai1998@gmail.com>
Date: Tue, 12 May 2026 19:24:41 -0600
Subject: [PATCH 1/4] bpf: Add canonical hash for BCF expressions

Adds bcf_canonical_hash(), a 64-bit SipHash-2-4 fingerprint of a BCF
expression DAG. Used at refinement sites to look up a precomputed proof
in the per-program BCF bundle (subsequent patches).

The hash satisfies: if __expr_equiv(a, b, from_checker=false,
own_args=false) == 1, then bcf_canonical_hash(a) == bcf_canonical_hash(b).
Equivalence is structural (matches BCF expr_equiv strength): same code,
vlen, params, recursively-equivalent args, with first-occurrence
renaming of variable expr-ids to handle bundle/kernel id-space drift.

Spec: docs/userspace-bcf/canonical-hash-spec.md (in the userspace
project repo). Userspace reference implementation lives there too, with
cross-impl agreement tests over a property-test corpus.

Implementation notes:
- Post-order walk linearised with an explicit stack (kernel stack budget).
- Slot-offset to array-index resolution via a small open-addressed table
  (mirrors verifier id_to_expr() over a flat buffer).
- Allocations are GFP_KERNEL kmalloc, freed on every return path.
- Errors: -EINVAL for malformed input, -E2BIG for excessive depth,
  -ENOMEM on allocation failure.
